{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_mike_ver02/data/sn83045433/0010049338A/1910092401/0109.xml":{"full_text":"WALL STREET NEWS\n\nReaction Follows the Com:\nparatively Large Rise,\n\n[snares\nPRETEXT FOR THE MOVEMENT\nNemarks of Mr. Lane, of the Inter\nstate Commerce Commission, Anent\nHigher Freight Rates, Cause Dis\ncouragement Interborough\u00abMet\nropolitan Stock Shows Rise,\n\n\ntg is\n\n\n\nNew York, Sept. 28.\u2014To-day the stock\nmarket was ripe for a reaction, in view\nof its comparatively large previous rise,\nand pretext for the declining movement\nwas found in published reports of the re\nmarks of My. Lane, a member of the\nInterstate Commerce Commission, at the\nhearing before the commission now go\ning on in Chicago upon the application\nof the railway companies for permission\nto make higher rates,\n\n\n\n\n\nPennsylvania 129\n\nsssasss Asked.\n\n\nOEE,\n10\n1\n\nMr. Lane was reported as saying that\nin his judgment, generally, the railway\ncompanies ought not to be allowed to\nmake higher rates, although it seems\ndoubtful if he would really put himself\nin the position thus of prejudicing a case\nwhich he was hearing. A quick drop in\nthe stock market followed shortly after\nthe opening of business, but, before noon,\nthe market steadied and was relatively\nstrong throughout the rest of the day.\nIt was recalled, so far as Mr. Lane was\nconcerned, that he was the one member\nof the Interstate Commerce Commission\nmost radical in his hostility to the rail\nroads, and that there were reasons for\nbelieving that his views in the present\nissue would not be controlling on those\nof his assoclates.\n185% 6% ie Ty\nAlldtislia al nomace os ANS Us\n(ity and Suburban 5s 1X N 12 i\nTip UN mbia Js PPP 101 102\ni i Columbia 6s 104\n5s 107\n\n\ni\n1'%\n13\nB%\n1\n128\n\nFRE\n107?\nV2\n4\ni\n\n\nRecovering Movement Seen.\nof\nof\nIn the recovering movement in the\nmarket, later in the day, the leadership\nwas assumed at various times by the\nReading, Interborough-Metropolitan, and\nAmerican Telephone and Telegraph\nshares. No particular reason was made\nknown for the upward movement in the\nlatter stock as well as the American\nTelephone and Telegraph convertible\nbonds, which has, however, been more\nor less conspicuous for some time.\n\n\n\nf\n\n\nIn the case of the Reading, explanation\nfor the rise was logically enough found\nin the publication to-day of the annual\nreport of the Central Railroad of New\nJersey, showing nearly 33% per cent\nearned in the year on the company's\ncapital stock, over one-half of which is\nowned by the Reading Company, before\ndeducting $4,000,000 set aside for additions\nand betterments.\n\n\ni\nThe rise in all the InterboroughMetro\npolitan stock and bond issues was based,\nas heretofore, on the practical certainty\nthat favorable developments regarding\nthe company's financial operations and\ngeneral! position are impending.\nM\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nNews Rather Favorable,\nFinancial news was again favorable\nrather than otherwise. A very sharp and\nseemingly unexpected break took place\nin the price of cotton, based upon a de\ncline in the quotation for the September\noption for the delivery of the commodity,\nwhich was said to be consequent upon\nthe tender of notices for the delivery of\nabout 10,000 bales in the present month.\n\n\n\n\ni M r\n\nIndications for to-morrow's bank state\nment were, of course, for another large\nloss in cash by the banks, owing to the\ncontinued shipment of money for agri\ncultural uses to the West and South\nwest with a fair, although in no way\nconsiderable, decrease in the bank sur\nplus, The general prospect of an easy\nmoney situation is such, however, that\ntime money continues to be offered at\nconcessions.\n\n\ni\n\n__\u2014_\nQuotations furnished by W, RB. Hibbs Co., mem.\nbers of the New York Stock Exchange, Hibbs Build.\n3:\n\nbe oF the Now York Stock \u2018Exchange, Hibbs Build:\nBid. Asked.\noe BEAMD A388 ersn