; straw, rye, machine thrash,\nLg wheat, per ton, 550; straw, oat, per\nQuotations furnished by W. B, Hibbs Co,\nmembers of the New York Stock Exchange, Hibbs\nBuilding.\nNew York, Sept. 23. \u2014The market broke to 5 and 8\npoints below yesterday's for the general list during\nthe last hour on further lijuidaticn and reselling by\ntraders, who bought on the advance yesterday and\nthis morring\u2019s further rise,\n1\nThe principal cause of this movement was the\nweakness displayed in the September option for the\nreasons stated in the carer rencort\nOOD ys clic ens venues s 13.35\nDecade enine PTR ARNE\nBEARER. oe vx caanzssennns vers 13.33\nNIL ere\nOpen.\nHigh.\n13.80\n13.38\n13.35\n13.32\n13.40\nWASHINGTON CATTLE MARKET,\nOCATTLE\u2014Extra, per cwt., 6.50a7.50; do., butcher,\n5.5026.00; commor, 4.50a5.00.\nHOGS\u2014Per cwt. gross, 9.50a10.00; do., ordinary,\n8.00,\nSHEEP\u2014-Prime, 250a4.00; do., common, 2.50a3.00.\nLAMBS\u2014Fancy spring, 6%al; fall, choice, per\nIb, 7; do., medium,\nCALVES\u2014Prime, per Ib, 910; do, medium, 8a\n8%; do., common, T.\nCOWS\u2014Prime fresh, each, 35.00845.00; do., com\nWow, &5.00a30.00; do., old and dry, 10.00a15.08,\nWEEKLY REVIEW OF TRADE\n\nDun and Bradstreet See Business Outlook Some\nwhat Mixed and Irresular.\n\ns\nNew York, Sept. 2.\u2014R. G. Dun Co.'s\nweekly review of trade to-morrow will\nsay:\n\u201cWith crops aggregating large in quan\ntity ang value, in spite of the reduced\nyield of sprig wheat; with politics be\ncoming so intense and uncertain as to\nmake enterprise timid, and with railroads\nand shippers engaged in a dispute over\nrates, the business outlook Is mixed,\ntrade reaction being very plain In some\nimportant directions, while at the same\ntime there are streaks of progress and\nactivity,\n\u201cAn interesgyng and, in its possible\noutcome, important development is the\nbetter demand for bonds. This is often\nan accompaniment of trade recession, but\nit is alse frequently the result of In\ncreased economies and, therefore, the\nforerunner of better times. Trade ad\nvices are of a mixed character. A num\nber of the leading cities report a move\nment larger than a week ago, and good\nseasonable weather has been especially\nbeneficial to retail business.\n\n\u201cIn dry-goods conditions are relatively\nmuch better than in most of the other\nlines.\n\u201cIn jron and steel, although there is\nconsiderable activity in the wire divi\nsion, the trade, as a whole, Is much be\nlow full mill capacity, and has suffered\nduring the past week by talk of price\nrecession, but this has met with official\ndenials.\n\u201cCommercial failures this week In the\nUnited States are 233, against 241 last\nweek; 2056 the preceding week, and 183 the\ncorresponding week last year. Fallures\nin Canada number 18, against 23 last\nweek; 22 the preceding week, and 37\nlast year.\u201d\nNEW YORK PRODUCE\nLOCAL PRODUCE MARKET.\n{Prices cuoted are wholesale.)\nBALTIMORE GKAIN MARKET.\nLOCAL GRAIN MARKET.\nCOTTON MARKET.\nNew York, Sept. 23\u2014Bradstreet's ra;\nview of the state of trade to-morrow will\nsay:\n\u201cTrade and Industrial reports are still\nIrregular and general characterization is\ndifficult. Fair activity in some lines and\nat some centers is indicated, but repres\nsion and conservatism are widely in evi\ndence and reflected in smal] but frequent\nrather than large or confident buying.\nj\n\u201cAmong favorable features may be\ncited the advance of the fall season,\nmore definite assurances as to yields of\nthe later planted crops, corn and cotton;\nfall festivals and the resumption of work\nby Western and Southwestern coal mineyg\nwho have been wholly or partially idle\nfor months past.\n\u201cOn the other side of the question there\nis witnessed the continuance of agitation\nof politico-economic questions, high levels\nof prices of commodities, and especially\nof raw materials of manufacture; short\ntime in industry, smal] profits reported\nin many lines, and in some sections the\ncontinuance of very warm weather which,\nwhile beneficial to crop development, acts\nas a bar to fullest activity in retail lines,\n\u201cOne really favorable underlying fea\nture, perhaps not thoroughly appreciated\nat present, {8 the apparent absence of\nlarge stocks of goods in primary or sec\nondary hands, born apparently of uncer\ntainty as to future prices and the growth\nof the bellef that far distant buying is\nnot either advisable or necessary. This\nwith the favorable crop outlook, will\nmake easier the resumption of fall ac\ntivity if other disturbing causes are re\nmoved.\u201d\nDAILY COURT RECORD.\n(Friday, September 23, 1010.)\nDISTRICT COURTS.\nEquity Court No. 1,\nCHIEF JUSTICE CLABAUGH.\nNo. 295, Prentiss vs. Rickards Wall Paper Com\npany; guardian ad litem appointed.\nIn re (lunacy) Charles L. Fhillips; reference to\nauditor,\nNo, 2660. Davis et al, vs, Newton;' decree sub\nstituting trustee. Attorney, G. C. Gertman,\nNo. 2913, Gordon vs, Norton; commission to\ntake testimony appointed. Attorueys, Erskine Gor\ndon\u2014A. 8. Worthington.\nNo. 206]. Kinyoun et al. va McCormick; decree\nsubstituting trustee, Attorneys, H. 8. Welch and\nD. C. Stutler.\nNo, 2%40, Leon ve. Dr. White; hearing on rule\ncontinued. Attorney, A. L. Newmyer.\nNo. 2812, Simpson vs, Simpeom; rule discharged.\nAttorneys, C., EK, Richards and Alfred D. Smith\nJ. 8. Easby-Smith,\nNo, 2815. Moore vs. Moore; restraining order and\nne exeat discharged. Attorneys, Maddox Gatley.\nNo. 2%3. Painton vs. International Auto Sight\nseeing Transit Company; rule returnable September\nZ, Attorneys, D. PP, Worthington and E. F. Callo\nday-Baker, Sheehy Hogan,\nNo, 23%6, Gunderson vs. Gunderson; same. At\ntorneys, W. 8S. Duvall and M. M. Desle-F. C.\nGeorge and M, E O'Brien.\nNo, 2765, Sands vs, Early; William J. Kehoe al\nlowed to interveme. Attorney, D. O'C, Callaghan,\nCireult Court No. 1.\nLRILD JL EN LLabalan,\nNo. 52876. First National Bank of Hyattsville ws,\nReady; order of pu